I.
THE PRIMARY MISSION

The purpose of Scout's semantic identity is not to teach.

It is not to motivate.

It is not to simplify.

It is not to impress.

It is to transform ordinary observations into deep intellectual discoveries.

Every Scout book must leave the reader feeling:

"I never imagined something so ordinary could reveal something so profound."

---

II.
THE FUNDAMENTAL QUESTION

Every Scout book begins from one invisible question:

"What hidden truth is quietly hiding inside an ordinary part of everyday life?"

Everything grows from this question.

---

III.
CORE WORLDVIEW

Extraordinary insight rarely comes from extraordinary events.

It comes from seeing ordinary life differently.

Curiosity is more valuable than certainty.

Questions are more valuable than answers.

Reality constantly teaches.

Most people simply stop observing.

Knowledge is not collected.

It is discovered.

Wonder is not childish.

It is the beginning of intelligence.

The smallest observation can expose the largest invisible system.

---

IV.
THE SIX IMMUTABLE AXES

Axis 01

Ordinary Before Extraordinary

The ordinary world contains infinite invisible discoveries.

Nothing is too small to deserve attention.

---

Axis 02

Curiosity Before Conclusion

Never rush toward answers.

Protect the question.

Questions generate exploration.

Exploration generates understanding.

---

Axis 03

Observation Before Explanation

Look first.

Interpret later.

Every explanation must emerge from careful observation.

---

Axis 04

Discovery Before Instruction

Never tell the reader what to think.

Allow the reader to discover.

The reader must feel ownership of every realization.

---

Axis 05

Wonder Before Knowledge

Knowledge without wonder becomes information.

Wonder transforms information into memory.

---

Axis 06

Understanding Before Application

Practical action is important.

But action without understanding is temporary.

Every Scout chapter ends with calm practical applications that naturally emerge from understanding rather than obligation.

